  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2019 by Peter Lang Verlag as part of the long-running <em>Reimagining Ireland</em> series, <em>The Great Irish Famine and Social Class</em>, edited by Marguerite Corporaal and Peter Gray, occupies a specialist but meaningful position within Famine studies. Available in open access, the volume has attracted citations from established journals in the field and holds a presence in library collections and commercial book platforms, signalling steady foundational utility for researchers and educators engaged with Irish history and social analysis.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The volume's most immediate strength lies in its commercial and institutional visibility. It is catalogued on both Amazon and Goodreads, extending its reach beyond the strictly academic sphere, while holdings in library collections confirm that the book has been acquired as a reference resource. Its open-access availability further removes cost barriers, broadening potential readership among students, independent researchers, and educators working with limited institutional budgets. These characteristics together position it as an accessible scholarly intervention rather than a narrowly circulated specialist monograph.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's citation record, though modest in absolute terms, is qualitatively significant. Both citing works appeared in 2022, approximately three years after publication \u2014 a pattern consistent with the slower citation cycles typical of humanities scholarship. Notably, one citation appears in <em>History Compass</em>, in a piece by Christine Kinealy of Quinnipiac University surveying new directions in Great Famine research, suggesting that the volume is being acknowledged as part of the active scholarly conversation about how the Famine is studied and framed. The second citation, in <em>Radical History Review</em>, engages themes of sympathy and social solidarity, thematically consonant with the book's central concern with class dynamics during the catastrophe. The volume's citation percentile score places it above nearly three-quarters of comparable works, a meaningful indicator given the book's relatively recent publication date and specialist subject matter.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Within the <em>Reimagining Ireland</em> series \u2014 a prolific Peter Lang imprint encompassing well over 140 volumes and continuing to produce new titles \u2014 Corporaal and Gray's contribution addresses a comparatively underexplored dimension of Famine historiography. Where much existing scholarship foregrounds ethnicity, religion, or colonial governance as primary analytical lenses, the explicit focus on social class offers a distinctive organising framework. The library subject headings assigned to the volume \u2014 covering famines, European social classes, human migration, and Irish history \u2014 reflect the interdisciplinary scope that characterises the best work in this tradition.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">At this stage of its citation life, <em>The Great Irish Famine and Social Class</em> is best characterised as a consolidating scholarly resource: grounded in a reputable series, engaged by active researchers in the field, and accessible to a wider audience through open access. Its trajectory suggests that as Famine studies continues to expand methodologically \u2014 incorporating approaches from social history, literary studies, and diaspora research \u2014 the volume's class-centred framework may attract growing critical attention from scholars seeking to move beyond established historiographical paradigms.</p>",
